#. <section class="sutta" id="sn2.25"><article><div class="hgroup"><p class="division">
msgctxt "sn2.25:0.1"
msgid "Saṃyutta Nikāya 2"
msgstr "Linked Discourses 2"

#. </p><p>
msgctxt "sn2.25:0.2"
msgid "3. Nānātitthiyavagga"
msgstr "3. Various Sectarians"

#. </p><h1>
msgctxt "sn2.25:0.3"
msgid "25. Jantusutta"
msgstr "25. With Jantu"

#. </h1></div><p>
#. <a class="pts1ed" id="pts1ed1.61"></a>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc1"></a>
msgctxt "sn2.25:1.1"
msgid "Evaṃ me sutaṃ—​"
msgstr "So I have heard."

# Surely the fact that several mendicants are staying there suggests that kutika doesn’t mean “little” hut?
msgctxt "sn2.25:1.2"
msgid ""
"ekaṃ samayaṃ sambahulā bhikkhū, kosalesu viharanti himavantapasse "
"araññakuṭikāya uddhatā unnaḷā capalā mukharā vikiṇṇavācā muṭṭhassatino "
"asampajānā asamāhitā vibbhantacittā pākatindriyā."
msgstr ""
"Now at that time several mendicants were staying in the Kosalan lands, in a "
"wilderness hut on the slopes of the Himalayas. They were restless, insolent, "
"fickle, gossipy, loose-tongued, unmindful, lacking situational awareness and "
"immersion, with straying minds and undisciplined faculties."

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc2"></a>
msgctxt "sn2.25:2.1"
msgid ""
"Atha kho jantu devaputto tadahuposathe pannarase yena te bhikkhū "
"tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā te bhikkhū gāthāhi ajjhabhāsi:"
msgstr ""
"Then on the fifteenth day sabbath the god Jantu went up to those mendicants "
"and addressed them in verse:"

#. </p><blockquote class="gatha"><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc3"></a>
msgctxt "sn2.25:3.1"
msgid "“Sukhajīvino pure āsuṃ,"
msgstr "“The mendicants used to live happily,"

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:3.2"
msgid "bhikkhū gotamasāvakā;"
msgstr "as disciples of Gotama."

#. <br>
#. VAR: piṇḍamesanā → piṇḍamesānā (pts2)
msgctxt "sn2.25:3.3"
msgid "Anicchā piṇḍamesanā,"
msgstr "Desireless they sought alms;"

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:3.4"
msgid "anicchā sayanāsanaṃ;"
msgstr "desireless they used their lodgings."

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:3.5"
msgid "Loke aniccataṃ ñatvā,"
msgstr "Knowing that the world was impermanent"

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:3.6"
msgid "dukkhassantaṃ akaṃsu te."
msgstr "they made an end of suffering."

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="pts2ed" id="pts2ed1.142"></a>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc4"></a>
msgctxt "sn2.25:4.1"
msgid "Dupposaṃ katvā attānaṃ,"
msgstr "But now they’ve made themselves hard to look after,"

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:4.2"
msgid "gāme gāmaṇikā viya;"
msgstr "like chiefs in a village."

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:4.3"
msgid "Bhutvā bhutvā nipajjanti,"
msgstr "They eat and eat and then lie down,"

# The comm interpretation of “infatuated”, followed by BB, is wrong. the point here is that they eat too much and fall asleep in houses, which is considered unbecoming conduct for a mendicant. Several Vinaya rules deal with related issues.
#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:4.4"
msgid "parāgāresu mucchitā."
msgstr "unconscious in the homes of others."

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc5"></a>
msgctxt "sn2.25:5.1"
msgid "Saṃghassa añjaliṃ katvā,"
msgstr "Having raised my joined palms to the Saṅgha,"

#. <br>
#. VAR: vadāmahaṃ → vandāmahaṃ (pts1, mr)
msgctxt "sn2.25:5.2"
msgid "idhekacce vadāmahaṃ;"
msgstr "I speak here only about certain people."

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:5.3"
msgid "Apaviddhā anāthā te,"
msgstr "They’re rejects, with no protector,"

#. <br>
#. VAR: tatheva te → tatheva ca (bj)
msgctxt "sn2.25:5.4"
msgid "yathā petā tatheva te."
msgstr "just like those who have passed away."

#. </p><p>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc6"></a>
msgctxt "sn2.25:6.1"
msgid "Ye kho pamattā viharanti,"
msgstr "I’m speaking about"

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:6.2"
msgid "te me sandhāya bhāsitaṃ;"
msgstr "those who live negligently."

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:6.3"
msgid "Ye appamattā viharanti,"
msgstr "To those who live diligently"

#. <br>
msgctxt "sn2.25:6.4"
msgid "namo tesaṃ karomahan”ti."
msgstr "I pay homage.”"
